  - title: "Carrier Scorecards — How to Hold Your Transportation Partners Accountable with Data"
    permalink: "https://runink.org/blog/carrier-scorecard-performance-management/"
    date: "2026-02-27T15:26:54Z"
    category: "blog"
    description: "Learn how carrier scorecards transform anecdotal carrier feedback into structured, data-driven performance management that improves OTD, reduces claims, and strengthens lane-level accountability."
    content: "What are the Key Takeaways from this Executive Summary? Quick Answer: A carrier scorecard is a systematic, data-driven tool that measures and compares carrier performance across standardized KPIs — replacing gut feelings and tribal knowledge with objective, repeatable evaluations. Shippers who implement structured scorecards gain leverage during rate negotiations, reduce service failures, and build carrier relationships grounded in mutual accountability rather than anecdotal feedback. Most shippers manage dozens of carriers without a structured evaluation framework. The result is that underperformers persist, top carriers are under-rewarded, and freight decisions are driven by relationships instead of results. Effective scorecards track weighted KPIs — on-time delivery, tender acceptance, claims ratio, billing accuracy — scored and reviewed on a defined cadence. Not all metrics carry equal weight, and the scoring methodology must reflect what actually matters to your network. Carriers prioritize shippers who measure and communicate performance. A transparent scorecard program signals operational maturity and gives carriers clear targets — creating a competitive dynamic that lifts service levels across your entire portfolio. What Is a Carrier Scorecard and Why Do Most Shippers Still Lack One? Quick Answer: A carrier scorecard is a standardized performance report that evaluates each transportation partner against a consistent set of KPIs — on-time delivery, claims ratio, tender acceptance, billing accuracy, and more — scored, weighted, and reviewed on a recurring cadence to drive accountability and inform procurement decisions. If you manage 30, 50, or 100+ carriers, you already know the problem. The account manager at your third-largest LTL provider insists their service is excellent. Your dock supervisors disagree. Your AP team flags billing discrepancies every cycle. And your customer service group is fielding complaints about late deliveries on a lane you thought was covered. Everyone has an opinion. Nobody has data.\nThat gap — between perception and performance — is exactly what a carrier scorecard is designed to close. According to the Council of Supply Chain Management Professionals (CSCMP), fewer than 40% of mid-market shippers operate a formalized carrier evaluation program, even though carrier performance is the single largest variable in OTIF (on-time, in-full) outcomes. The rest rely on quarterly check-ins, relationship history, and the occasional escalation email.\nThe cost of this approach is invisible until it compounds. Underperforming carriers hold onto lanes they should lose. High-performing carriers receive no recognition — and no incentive to prioritize your freight when capacity tightens. Rate negotiations happen without performance context, leaving millions on the table. A scorecard does not fix every carrier problem, but it creates the foundation for every conversation that does.\nWhich Metrics Belong on a Carrier Scorecard? Quick Answer: The essential carrier scorecard metrics include on-time pickup percentage, on-time delivery percentage, claims ratio, tender acceptance rate, EDI compliance, billing accuracy, transit time variability, and damage rate — each capturing a distinct dimension of carrier reliability, communication, and financial integrity. Not every metric matters equally, but every metric on this list earns its place by answering a specific operational question:\nOn-time pickup % and on-time delivery % (OTD). These are the foundational service metrics. OTD measures whether your carrier does the one thing you hired them to do — move freight from origin to destination within the agreed window. Industry benchmarks from Gartner\u0026rsquo;s TMS research suggest that best-in-class shippers target 95%+ OTD across their carrier base, with top carriers consistently exceeding 97%.\nTender acceptance rate. When you tender a load, does the carrier accept it? A carrier with a 70% acceptance rate is not a reliable partner — they are a backup option masquerading as a primary. Low tender acceptance forces you into the spot market, where rates can spike 30-50% above contract. This metric is especially critical during peak season and capacity crunches.\nClaims ratio and damage rate. Cargo claims are expensive, time-consuming, and a direct signal of handling quality. Track both the frequency (claims per 100 shipments) and the severity (average claim value). The American Trucking Associations reports that cargo claims remain one of the top five cost drivers for shippers managing FTL and LTL programs.\nBilling accuracy. If your freight audit team is correcting 8-12% of invoices from a given carrier, that is not an accounting nuisance — it is a systemic data quality problem that inflates freight spend and erodes trust. Billing accuracy below 95% should trigger a formal review.\nEDI compliance. Status updates, shipment milestones, proof of delivery — EDI compliance measures whether a carrier communicates reliably through your TMS. Poor EDI compliance creates visibility black holes that cascade into customer service failures and planning errors.\nTransit time variability. Average transit time matters less than consistency. A carrier that delivers in 2.1 days on average but swings between 1.5 and 4 days is harder to plan around than one averaging 2.5 days with a tight standard deviation. MIT FreightLab research has consistently demonstrated that transit time variability is a stronger predictor of supply chain disruption than average transit time alone.\nHow Should You Weight and Score Carrier Performance? Quick Answer: Not all KPIs are equal. Effective scorecards assign weighted scores that reflect each shipper\u0026rsquo;s operational priorities — typically weighting OTD and tender acceptance highest, followed by claims and billing accuracy, with EDI compliance and transit variability as supporting metrics. A flat, unweighted scorecard treats EDI compliance the same as on-time delivery. That produces misleading results. A carrier scoring 99% on EDI but 88% on OTD should not rank above a carrier scoring 96% OTD with moderate EDI gaps. The weighting must reflect your network\u0026rsquo;s actual pain points.\nA common starting framework allocates weights as follows: OTD (30%), tender acceptance (20%), claims ratio (15%), billing accuracy (15%), transit time variability (10%), and EDI compliance (10%). But these weights are not universal. A shipper running a just-in-time automotive supply chain will weight transit variability far higher than a bulk commodities shipper. A retailer managing peak-season surge capacity will elevate tender acceptance above all else.\nThe scoring model itself should be simple enough for carrier account managers to understand. A 100-point scale works well — each carrier earns a composite score that maps to a performance tier: Preferred (90+), Approved (75-89), Probation (60-74), and Exit (below 60). These tiers should carry real consequences: preferred carriers receive first-right-of-refusal on new lanes and volume commitments; probation carriers receive a 90-day improvement plan with defined targets; exit-tier carriers are removed from the routing guide.\nWhat Is the Right Cadence for Scorecard Reviews? Quick Answer: Best-in-class shipper programs operate on a three-tier cadence: monthly scorecards for operational tracking, quarterly business reviews (QBRs) for strategic alignment, and annual performance evaluations tied to contract renewals and rate negotiations. Monthly scorecards are the operational heartbeat. They provide carrier account teams with a rolling performance snapshot — no surprises, no ambiguity. When a carrier\u0026rsquo;s OTD drops from 96% to 91% in a given month, the scorecard captures it immediately, enabling a targeted conversation before the problem becomes a pattern.\nQuarterly business reviews elevate the discussion from individual metrics to strategic alignment. QBRs are where you review lane-level performance trends, discuss capacity commitments, address systemic issues like billing disputes or claims patterns, and align on upcoming demand forecasts. This is also where you share your scorecard methodology transparently — carriers who understand exactly how they are measured will optimize toward those metrics.\nAnnual evaluations tie performance to procurement. When contract renewal season arrives, your scorecard data becomes your negotiating leverage. A carrier sitting at 93 composite with strong tender acceptance has earned rate stability. A carrier at 72 composite with declining OTD and rising claims has not — and your data makes that case objectively.\nHow Do Scorecards Actually Change Carrier Behavior? Quick Answer: Carriers allocate capacity, assign drivers, and prioritize service based on which shippers measure performance and communicate expectations clearly. A structured scorecard program signals that your freight matters — and that accountability flows in both directions. This is the insight that transforms a scorecard from a reporting exercise into a strategic tool: carriers respond to measurement. When a carrier knows that their tender acceptance rate is tracked and that falling below 85% triggers a lane reallocation, they adjust dispatch priorities accordingly. When they know that billing errors above 5% result in a QBR escalation, their invoicing team tightens processes. Measurement creates incentives. Incentives drive behavior.\nThe reverse is equally true. Shippers who do not measure carrier performance signal that service quality is negotiable. During capacity crunches — the exact moments when carrier performance matters most — those shippers are the first to see loads rejected, deliveries delayed, and spot rates quoted at premiums.\nThis is also where automation becomes essential. Manually compiling scorecard data from TMS exports, ERP billing records, claims databases, and EDI logs is a full-time job — and the delay between data collection and scorecard delivery erodes the program\u0026rsquo;s value. By the time a manually assembled scorecard lands in a carrier\u0026rsquo;s inbox, the performance it reflects is six weeks old.\nPlatforms like Runink eliminate that lag by ingesting live data from TMS, ERP, and WMS systems to generate carrier scorecards automatically — scored, weighted, and benchmarked against lane-specific performance baselines. When a carrier\u0026rsquo;s OTD drops below your defined threshold on a specific lane, Runink triggers an automated alert to both your procurement team and the carrier\u0026rsquo;s account manager, compressing the feedback loop from weeks to hours. The result is a scorecard program that operates at the speed of your freight, not the speed of your spreadsheet.\nConclusion Quick Answer: Carrier scorecards are the most underutilized lever in transportation management. They convert subjective opinions into objective performance data, create accountability structures that improve service levels, and provide the analytical foundation for smarter procurement decisions. The shippers who win in competitive freight markets are not necessarily the ones moving the most volume. They are the ones who know — with precision — which carriers are earning their lanes and which are coasting on inertia. A structured scorecard program, backed by weighted KPIs, a defined review cadence, and real consequences for underperformance, is how you build that knowledge into your operation.\nThe question is not whether you should measure carrier performance. The question is whether you can afford the cost of not measuring it — in missed deliveries, inflated claims, wasted spot spend, and eroded customer confidence. Runink helps transportation leaders automate carrier scorecards from live operational data, turning performance management from a quarterly exercise into a continuous competitive advantage.\n"
